The convective and radiative HTs to the surroundings are considered in the TM as boundary conditions for Eq. (6). The PC's HT rate per unit area, denoted as 

                                 q
                                 ˙

                           , is used to calculate these boundary conditions. The convective HT coefficient, ℎ, is also included in the calculations, as well as the local Temp on the surface of the PC (Tsurf
                           ), ambient Temp (Tamb
                           ), the Stefan-Boltzmann constant (σ), and emissivity (E).

To accurately apply the energy balance Eq to the different layers of a PC, it is crucial to use the appropriate thermal parameters, such as TC, heat capacity (HC), and density. The current collectors are typically composed of copper or aluminum. At the same time, the AM layers and outer layers are non-homogeneous and treated as a single material for HT purposes. Therefore, the effective conductivity of these layered materials must be determined. Since the AMs are layered, two effective conductivities are required: one perpendicular to the layers (denoted as kser
                           ) and one parallel to the layers (denoted as kpar
                           ). Fig. 5
                            depicts the parallel and series thermal circuits that calculate effective conductivities based on thermal resistances for two AM layers. Similar parallel and series effective conductivities are computed for the PC's outer layers.
